00:02:35,955 --> 00:02:40,688
GATES: In the early morning
of April 12,1861,

44
00:02:40,760 --> 00:02:44,662
South em cannons opened fire
on Fort Sumter,

45
00:02:44,731 --> 00:02:49,065
A federal garrison
in Charleston Harbor.

46
00:02:49,135 --> 00:02:52,536
The North and South were at war.

47
00:03:01,514 --> 00:03:04,005
When the Civil War began,

48
00:03:04,083 --> 00:03:09,350
more than 3.9 million slaves
faced a terrible choice--

49
00:03:09,422 --> 00:03:13,586
to be forced to aid
a Confederate army they despised

50
00:03:13,660 --> 00:03:17,596
or gamble everything on escape.

51
00:03:17,664 --> 00:03:21,600
Half a million chose
to break and run.

52
00:03:21,668 --> 00:03:24,102
Not only would they change
the tide of war,

53
00:03:24,170 --> 00:03:28,607
they would change its meaning,
turning a war about union

54
00:03:28,675 --> 00:03:31,075
into a war about slavery.

55
00:03:33,346 --> 00:03:36,372
One of my favorite stories
of the Civil War happened

56
00:03:36,449 --> 00:03:38,883
right here at the battery
just a year

57
00:03:38,952 --> 00:03:42,888
after the outbreak of the war
over at Fort Sumter.

58
00:03:42,956 --> 00:03:47,393
As Charleston slept,
a young black man, a slave,

59
00:03:47,460 --> 00:03:50,861
plotted his escape
aboard a ship.

60
00:03:52,966 --> 00:03:56,868
Robert Smalls
was a 23-year-old slave

61
00:03:56,936 --> 00:03:59,564
pressed into service
for the Confederacy

62
00:03:59,639 --> 00:04:02,233
aboard a warship called
the Planter.

63
00:04:03,509 --> 00:04:06,444
For nearly a year,
he quietly observed

64
00:04:06,512 --> 00:04:09,606
the movements of the ship
and its crew.

65
00:04:09,682 --> 00:04:14,119
Just before dawn
on May 13, 1862,

66
00:04:14,187 --> 00:04:17,623
Smalls took his chance.

67
00:04:17,690 --> 00:04:20,625
While the ship's officers
slept ashore,

68
00:04:20,693 --> 00:04:23,628
he and his fellow slave crewmen
pulled anchor

69
00:04:23,696 --> 00:04:27,291
and eased the Planter
into Charleston Harbor.

70
00:04:27,367 --> 00:04:31,861
MAN: They had prearranged
to meet their family members

71
00:04:31,938 --> 00:04:35,203
and to pick them up,
and then come back

72
00:04:35,275 --> 00:04:39,177
down the peninsula
and they begin the process,

73
00:04:39,245 --> 00:04:41,509
and this is in the wee
hours of the morning

74
00:04:41,581 --> 00:04:44,277
of sailing out of
the harbor.

75
00:04:44,350 --> 00:04:49,253
They are embarked now on
an extremely dangerous journey.

76
00:04:51,357 --> 00:04:54,622
GATES: Smalls knew these waters
like the back of his hand,

77
00:04:54,694 --> 00:04:57,629
but he also knew the risks
that lay ahead--

78
00:04:57,697 --> 00:05:00,495
4 Confederate checkpoints:

79
00:05:00,566 --> 00:05:04,024
Castle Pinckney, Fort Ripley,

80
00:05:04,103 --> 00:05:07,402
Fort Johnson,
and Fort Sumter.

81
00:05:07,473 --> 00:05:09,907
Isn't Smalls afraid
of being caught?

82
00:05:09,976 --> 00:05:11,705
How in the world
is a black slave

83
00:05:11,778 --> 00:05:13,211
gonna pull this off?

84
00:05:13,279 --> 00:05:15,839
He's extremely afraid
of being caught.

85
00:05:15,915 --> 00:05:18,679
He disguises himself
<i>as</i> the captain

86
00:05:18,751 --> 00:05:21,413
and also mimics
the captain's gait

87
00:05:21,487 --> 00:05:24,581
as he walked back and forth
across the wheelhouse.

88
00:05:24,657 --> 00:05:30,425
GATES: Smalls slipped past the
first 3 checkpoints undetected.

89
00:05:30,496 --> 00:05:33,932
The most dangerous
checkpoint remained--

90
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:36,935
Fort Sumter,
with its mighty guns

91
00:05:37,003 --> 00:05:39,437
and fearsome cannons.

92
00:05:39,505 --> 00:05:43,407
Discovery would mean
certain death.

93
00:05:45,044 --> 00:05:46,636
As dawn broke,

94
00:05:46,713 --> 00:05:49,648
the crew urged Smalls
to take a wide berth,

95
00:05:49,716 --> 00:05:53,709
but changing course
could arouse suspicion.

96
00:05:53,786 --> 00:05:55,879
Smalls gave the signal.

97
00:05:55,955 --> 00:05:58,856
[Steam whistle blowing]

98
00:06:03,596 --> 00:06:06,861
A few seconds later,
the countersignal came back.

99
00:06:06,933 --> 00:06:10,733
[Steam whistle blows]

100
00:06:10,803 --> 00:06:13,237
"Pass on by."

101
00:06:13,306 --> 00:06:15,740
So they're safe, right?
They're free?

102
00:06:15,808 --> 00:06:18,868
Well, they're not
completely free

103
00:06:18,945 --> 00:06:21,379
because now we have
this situation where

104
00:06:21,447 --> 00:06:25,383
a Confederate-ﬂagged
vessel is sailing out,

105
00:06:25,451 --> 00:06:28,215
and it begins
to approach the vessels

106
00:06:28,287 --> 00:06:31,723
of the Union naval
blockading force.

107
00:06:31,791 --> 00:06:35,852
GATES: Fortunately,
the vessel was not fired on.

108
00:06:35,928 --> 00:06:39,455
As astonished Union officers
boarded the Planter,

109
00:06:39,532 --> 00:06:43,468
Smalls stood at attention,
saluted, and spoke.

110
00:06:43,536 --> 00:06:47,131
POWERS: "I am delivering
this war materiel,

111
00:06:47,206 --> 00:06:50,471
"including these cannons,
and I think

112
00:06:50,543 --> 00:06:54,070
Uncle Abraham Lincoln
can put them to good use."

113
00:06:54,147 --> 00:06:55,842
Ha ha ha!
Ha ha ha!

114
00:06:55,915 --> 00:06:58,645
Smalls was ready with
his line for history.

115
00:06:58,718 --> 00:07:00,618
That's right.
That's right.

116
00:07:02,155 --> 00:07:04,817
GATES: "I don't know exactly
what you are now,"

117
00:07:04,891 --> 00:07:06,825
the officer told Smalls,

118
00:07:06,893 --> 00:07:09,794
"but you're certainly
no longer slaves."

119
00:07:21,140 --> 00:07:24,735
Robert Smalls' escape
personified a new,

120
00:07:24,811 --> 00:07:28,907
more determined attitude
among Southern slaves.

121
00:07:28,981 --> 00:07:33,816
Before the war, his bold act
would have been in vain.

122
00:07:33,886 --> 00:07:36,320
The Fugitive Slave Act of 1850

123
00:07:36,389 --> 00:07:38,016
decreed that runaway slaves

124
00:07:38,090 --> 00:07:40,024
were to be hunted down

125
00:07:40,092 --> 00:07:44,028
and returned to their masters
in chains,

126
00:07:44,096 --> 00:07:48,032
but all that changed
on May 23,1861,

127
00:07:48,100 --> 00:07:51,035
less than a year
before Smalls' escape,

128
00:07:51,103 --> 00:07:56,040
when 3 runaway slaves made it
here to Fort Monroe,

129
00:07:56,108 --> 00:08:00,135
a Union-held outpost
in Confederate Virginia.

130
00:08:00,213 --> 00:08:01,976
The slaves were taken before

131
00:08:02,048 --> 00:08:05,040
Union Major General
Benjamin Butler.

132
00:08:05,117 --> 00:08:08,052
Defying the law, Butler refused

133
00:08:08,120 --> 00:08:11,556
to return the fugitive slaves
to the Confederacy.

134
00:08:11,624 --> 00:08:15,219
Instead, he invented
a new status for them.

135
00:08:15,294 --> 00:08:17,728
They were contraband of war,

136
00:08:17,797 --> 00:08:22,291
illegal property now forfeited
to the North.

137
00:08:22,368 --> 00:08:27,305
Butler could have no idea
how wide a door he had opened.

138
00:08:27,373 --> 00:08:31,036
MAN: The Contraband Act
doesn't legally free them,

139
00:08:31,110 --> 00:08:33,101
but if you're a slave
on the ground

140
00:08:33,179 --> 00:08:37,047
and you reach Union lines,
that act says

141
00:08:37,116 --> 00:08:39,175
that the officer
is required

142
00:08:39,252 --> 00:08:41,015
to retain you,
put you to work.

143
00:08:41,087 --> 00:08:42,486
In practice, you're ﬂee.

144
00:08:50,897 --> 00:08:53,525
GATES: The word went out
through the slaves' grapevine,

145
00:08:53,599 --> 00:08:57,194
and all these Negroes
descend upon Fort Monroe.

146
00:08:57,270 --> 00:08:59,135
I bet the Army didn't
know what hit them.

147
00:08:59,205 --> 00:09:01,969
No, they didn't, and they
didn't know what to do.

148
00:09:02,041 --> 00:09:05,533
Hundreds came over here,
and they were located

149
00:09:05,611 --> 00:09:08,739
in and around the fort.

150
00:09:08,814 --> 00:09:12,181
So there were all these
makeshift camps everywhere.

151
00:09:12,251 --> 00:09:15,243
Dysentery was very common,

152
00:09:15,321 --> 00:09:17,789
tuberculosis,

153
00:09:17,857 --> 00:09:20,655
all kinds of diseases.

154
00:09:20,726 --> 00:09:23,957
It was a horrendous
situation.

155
00:09:24,030 --> 00:09:26,863
GATES: Neither slave nor free,

156
00:09:26,933 --> 00:09:29,299
the contraband
had found sanctuary,

157
00:09:29,368 --> 00:09:31,962
but were little more
than refugees,

158
00:09:32,038 --> 00:09:34,131
a burden to the war effort

159
00:09:34,206 --> 00:09:38,438
in the eyes of some
Northern soldiers.

160
00:09:38,511 --> 00:09:42,106
We can't imagine,
I don't think, the cost,

161
00:09:42,181 --> 00:09:45,617
the courage,
the difficulty

162
00:09:45,685 --> 00:09:48,085
of making that journey
and getting there

163
00:09:48,154 --> 00:09:52,591
and some commander saying,
"OK, we have to take them in,

164
00:09:52,658 --> 00:09:54,626
"but don't give them food

165
00:09:54,694 --> 00:09:57,629
because that will
make them lazy."

166
00:09:57,697 --> 00:10:01,599
GATES: Still, the escaped slaves
kept coming

167
00:10:01,667 --> 00:10:05,501
in a great upsurge
of hope and courage.

168
00:10:12,078 --> 00:10:15,980
Although their status remained
as uncertain at the war itself,

169
00:10:16,048 --> 00:10:20,508
the contraband sought to live
as fully free men and women.

170
00:10:20,586 --> 00:10:23,521
Even in the midst
of squalid camps,

171
00:10:23,589 --> 00:10:27,025
they pursued a privilege
long denied to slaves-

172
00:10:27,093 --> 00:10:29,493
learning to read and write.

173
00:10:32,098 --> 00:10:34,760
Some contraband began
their education here

174
00:10:34,834 --> 00:10:38,235
on what is today the campus
of Hampton University,

175
00:10:38,304 --> 00:10:41,535
one of the country's oldest
black colleges.

176
00:10:41,607 --> 00:10:44,542
It was all made possible

177
00:10:44,610 --> 00:10:48,205
by a visionary teacher
named Mary Peake.

178
00:10:48,280 --> 00:10:50,373
For Peake,

179
00:10:50,449 --> 00:10:52,713
an educated woman of color,

180
00:10:52,785 --> 00:10:56,551
liberating the mind was as
important as freeing the body.

181
00:10:56,622 --> 00:11:01,389
Before the war,
she had taught slaves in secret,

182
00:11:01,460 --> 00:11:04,122
Defying the law,

183
00:11:04,196 --> 00:11:07,723
but in Union-occupied
Hampton, Virginia,

184
00:11:07,800 --> 00:11:10,667
those laws no longer applied.

185
00:11:12,271 --> 00:11:14,205
Peaks conducted her lessons

186
00:11:14,273 --> 00:11:16,707
beneath the branches
of this oak tree,

187
00:11:16,776 --> 00:11:20,212
which, incredibly,
still stands today.

188
00:11:20,279 --> 00:11:23,214
No one even knew
at the beginning of the war

189
00:11:23,282 --> 00:11:25,546
if a Union victory
would even lead

190
00:11:25,618 --> 00:11:27,711
to the abolition
of slavery.
GLYMPH: No.

191
00:11:27,787 --> 00:11:29,345
GATES: So why
would she do it?

192
00:11:29,422 --> 00:11:32,357
GLYMPH: I think that,
like a lot of blacks,

193
00:11:32,425 --> 00:11:34,791
she saw this
as an opportunity.

194
00:11:34,860 --> 00:11:38,296
She was passionate
about using her skills,

195
00:11:38,364 --> 00:11:40,798
her talents
and abilities

196
00:11:40,866 --> 00:11:43,733
to help uplift
the community.

197
00:11:43,803 --> 00:11:46,738
GATES: Mary Peake's
contraband students

198
00:11:46,806 --> 00:11:49,741
let nothing keep them
from learning.

199
00:11:49,809 --> 00:11:52,642
GLYMPH : There was
a mother and a daughter.

200
00:11:52,712 --> 00:11:54,646
They were living
in this tent.

201
00:11:54,714 --> 00:11:57,649
They had one dress
between the two of them,

202
00:11:57,717 --> 00:12:00,311
and so, during the day,
the daughter

203
00:12:00,386 --> 00:12:03,116
would wear the dress
and go to school

204
00:12:03,189 --> 00:12:05,282
and then come back
afierschooL

205
00:12:05,357 --> 00:12:07,791
and the mother would
then do some work

206
00:12:07,860 --> 00:12:09,794
and then go
to night school.

207
00:12:09,862 --> 00:12:10,794
Hmm.

208
00:12:10,863 --> 00:12:12,797
So they shared
a single dress

209
00:12:12,865 --> 00:12:14,696
between the two of them.

210
00:12:14,767 --> 00:12:18,703
How quickly does
her school grow?

211
00:12:18,771 --> 00:12:21,205
It starts
with a handful,

212
00:12:21,273 --> 00:12:23,207
but then quickly,
there are 50.

213
00:12:23,275 --> 00:12:25,766
Then there are
a hundred.
Mm-hmm.

214
00:12:25,845 --> 00:12:28,075
She ended up
with 900 students.

215
00:12:28,147 --> 00:12:30,047
900 students.

216
00:12:32,151 --> 00:12:34,244
What she
was trying to do

217
00:12:34,320 --> 00:12:36,413
was to prepare
people

218
00:12:36,489 --> 00:12:39,322
to really be
full citizens.

219
00:12:43,262 --> 00:12:46,698
GATES: Escaped slaves
were changing their own lives,

220
00:12:46,766 --> 00:12:51,226
but they were also transforming
the fate of the nation.

221
00:12:51,303 --> 00:12:53,737
By the summer of 1862,

222
00:12:53,806 --> 00:12:56,741
President Lincoln
faced a dilemma.

223
00:12:56,809 --> 00:12:59,869
Not only was the North
losing the war,

224
00:12:59,945 --> 00:13:03,881
but runaway slaves were forcing
him finally to confront

225
00:13:03,949 --> 00:13:07,112
the question of slavery itself.

226
00:13:07,186 --> 00:13:10,121
Lincoln's first objective
in the war

227
00:13:10,189 --> 00:13:12,123
had been to save the Union.

228
00:13:12,191 --> 00:13:14,785
"I have no purpose,"
he had proclaimed,

229
00:13:14,860 --> 00:13:19,297
"to interfere with
the institution of slavery."

230
00:13:19,365 --> 00:13:22,459
But now, military necessity
converged

231
00:13:22,535 --> 00:13:26,437
with the moral imperative
of ending slavery.

232
00:13:28,541 --> 00:13:31,476
GATES: This was
the country in 1862.

233
00:13:31,544 --> 00:13:34,479
GLYMPH: It <i>was,</i> and,
therefore, for Lincoln,

234
00:13:34,547 --> 00:13:37,175
a place he could escape to.

235
00:13:37,249 --> 00:13:40,184
He came here pretty often
in the summer

236
00:13:40,252 --> 00:13:42,550
of '62, which is
his critical summer

237
00:13:42,621 --> 00:13:44,555
where he was writing
the Proclamation.

238
00:13:44,623 --> 00:13:46,056
This is Camp David.

239
00:13:46,125 --> 00:13:49,117
This is his Camp David.

240
00:13:49,195 --> 00:13:51,629
As he wrote
and made the journey

241
00:13:51,697 --> 00:13:54,495
to this cottage,
he would have seen

242
00:13:54,567 --> 00:13:57,434
black refugees camped out
all over the city.

243
00:13:57,503 --> 00:14:01,030
What do you do with them?
Do you just keep ignoring them?

244
00:14:01,106 --> 00:14:05,907
Enslaved people were
making the war their war.

245
00:14:05,978 --> 00:14:09,914
They were making
the war about freedom
and emancipation.

246
00:14:09,982 --> 00:14:13,418
