of literacy tests,

825
00:46:44,601 --> 00:46:47,536
knowing that they would
effectively bar black men

826
00:46:47,604 --> 00:46:50,539
<i>from voting in Mississippi.</i>

827
00:46:50,607 --> 00:46:54,043
It was a bargain that would
reverberate across the South

828
00:46:54,111 --> 00:46:56,079
for decades to come.

829
00:46:57,681 --> 00:47:03,677
He said, "I'm willing
to sacrifice 123,000 men

830
00:47:03,754 --> 00:47:06,689
in order that
white people will give us
some breathing room."

831
00:47:06,757 --> 00:47:08,691
Mm-hmm.
"We will stand back

832
00:47:08,759 --> 00:47:12,195
"and let you have
the political arena.

833
00:47:12,262 --> 00:47:14,355
"We will let you have
the franchise.

834
00:47:14,431 --> 00:47:18,424
Just give us a little bit
of room so that we can,
you know, do a few things."

835
00:47:18,502 --> 00:47:21,596
Isaiah himself acknowledged
that it was a compromise,

836
00:47:21,672 --> 00:47:24,607
but on the other hand,
you have to understand

837
00:47:24,675 --> 00:47:27,667
the South and, particularly,
Mississippi at the time.

838
00:47:27,744 --> 00:47:31,180
There is a lynching
in the South every--

839
00:47:31,248 --> 00:47:33,842
it's either third day
or fourth day.
Mmm.

840
00:47:33,917 --> 00:47:37,353
He needs to do everything
he can to ensure

841
00:47:37,421 --> 00:47:40,219
that whites aren't
gonna get outraged

842
00:47:40,290 --> 00:47:44,226
and have a reason
for torching

843
00:47:44,294 --> 00:47:46,228
and burning his community.
Mm-hmm.

844
00:47:46,296 --> 00:47:50,892
And one reason is to say,
"OK, I'll accept your
disenfranchisement.

845
00:47:50,968 --> 00:47:56,668
I just want to
retain my autonomous
black community."

846
00:47:56,740 --> 00:48:00,608
So...was it possible?

847
00:48:00,677 --> 00:48:04,340
Was there a scenario
that you imagine

848
00:48:04,414 --> 00:48:07,349
where their logic
made sense?

849
00:48:07,417 --> 00:48:11,353
In the United States
of America,

850
00:48:11,421 --> 00:48:14,857
which purports to be
a democracy, the notion

851
00:48:14,925 --> 00:48:17,985
that you would have
to give up your freedom

852
00:48:18,061 --> 00:48:20,962
to become ﬂee, it just
doesn't make any sense.

853
00:48:21,031 --> 00:48:24,967
Or that you can bargain
away the future freedoms

854
00:48:25,035 --> 00:48:29,972
of people by giving up
current rights,

855
00:48:30,040 --> 00:48:32,975
I think it was...

856
00:48:33,043 --> 00:48:35,170
like a devil's pact.

857
00:48:35,245 --> 00:48:38,442
You can do it
and hope that, "OK,

858
00:48:38,515 --> 00:48:41,450
you know, we accommodate some,
they'll treat us better,"

859
00:48:41,518 --> 00:48:43,419
but they won't,
and they did not.

860
00:48:43,420 --> 00:48:44,478
But they won't,
and they did not.

861
00:48:54,264 --> 00:48:57,700
GATES: As Southern legislatures
mounted a relentless assault

862
00:48:57,768 --> 00:49:01,204
on their hard-won rights,
African Americans devised

863
00:49:01,271 --> 00:49:04,502
new strategies
to hold on to the gains

864
00:49:04,574 --> 00:49:08,010
they had made
during Reconstruction.

865
00:49:08,078 --> 00:49:11,138
On June 7,1892,

866
00:49:11,214 --> 00:49:13,648
Homer Plessy strode
through the streets

867
00:49:13,717 --> 00:49:16,652
of his native New Orleans
toward the train station.

868
00:49:16,720 --> 00:49:19,154
[Train bell clanging]

869
00:49:19,222 --> 00:49:22,089
This was no idle stroll.

870
00:49:22,159 --> 00:49:25,595
He was about to test
the 14th Amendment's promise

871
00:49:25,662 --> 00:49:28,597
of equal protection
under the law.

872
00:49:28,665 --> 00:49:30,963
He would board
a white passenger car

873
00:49:31,034 --> 00:49:34,561
and refuse to move
to the black one.

874
00:49:34,638 --> 00:49:37,573
GATES: OK, June 7,1892,

875
00:49:37,641 --> 00:49:39,700
the Press Street depot.

876
00:49:39,776 --> 00:49:42,711
What is Homer Plessy
doing there?

877
00:49:42,779 --> 00:49:44,713
Homer Plessy is
attempting to be

878
00:49:44,781 --> 00:49:48,717
arrested, booked,
and tried

879
00:49:48,785 --> 00:49:51,720
for violating the
segregation laws
of 1890.

880
00:49:51,788 --> 00:49:53,221
I don't think he was
very confident

881
00:49:53,290 --> 00:49:55,724
that he wouldn't be
hung that day

882
00:49:55,792 --> 00:49:58,226
because there was
a serious plan in effect

883
00:49:58,295 --> 00:50:01,355
to actually orchestrate
his arrest.
Mm-hmm.

884
00:50:01,431 --> 00:50:03,365
[Bell clan gs]

885
00:50:03,433 --> 00:50:06,368
GATES: Conceived by a group
of black Republicans,

886
00:50:06,436 --> 00:50:11,032
Plessy's gambit was a calculated
act of civil disobedience--

887
00:50:11,108 --> 00:50:15,545
breaking Louisiana's law
in the hope of landing the case

888
00:50:15,612 --> 00:50:18,479
in the United States
Supreme Court.

889
00:50:18,548 --> 00:50:20,641
The group had chosen
Homer Plessy

890
00:50:20,717 --> 00:50:23,151
for one overriding reason:

891
00:50:23,220 --> 00:50:25,552
